      <div class='hentry member_contribution'>
        <a name='S6CV0379P0_20020131_WH_25'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-peter-hain' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S6CV0379P0_20020131_WH_25' title='Link to this speech by Mr Peter Hain' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-peter-hain" title="Mr Peter Hain">Peter Hain</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            I shall respond to the hon. Gentleman in some detail, as this is an important point. I refer him to the background. The European Council asked us to take forward the Brussels process discussions in the interests of all concerned. The Government of Gibraltar left Britain and Spain with no alternative but to see whether we could agree proposals, as we were the only parties that could do so when the Chief Minister left an empty chair. Now that the Government of Gibraltar realise that their attempted veto has failed and that the talks must proceed because the European Council requested us to reach a conclusion if possible, people seem to be saying that we should create a second veto instead of filling that empty chair.</p><p>
            As I understand the point made by the hon. Member for Rochford and Southend, East (Sir T. Taylor), any proposal that emerged from the Brussels process is supposed to vanish as if it had never appeared, in the way that communist governments air-brushed events from their history books. Any proposals that emerge will be just that&#x2014;proposals. If they are put to a referendum and rejected, no one can air-brush them away, but they cannot be implemented. I remind the Committee that in 1994, under a similar line of attack, the Conservative Secretary of State for Northern Ireland was asked about the status of the Downing Street declaration that was agreed between the Governments of Britain and Ireland. He told the House that
            <q>The declaration remains, and will remain, a free-standing declaration of principles."&#x2014;[<a href="/commons/1994/apr/28/electricity#column_375"><span class="italic">Official Report,</span> 28 April 1994; Vol. 242, c. 375.</a>]</q>
            That was greeted with outrage from some quarters, but led eventually to the Good Friday agreement of 1998, which has brought peace and stability to Northern Ireland when none looked possible. The short answer to the hon. Gentleman's question is that one cannot air-
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_142wh' title='Col. 142WH &mdash; HC Deb 31 January 2002 vol 379 c142WH' name='column_142wh' href='#column_142wh' rel='bookmark'>142WH</a>
            brush the joint declaration away, but it cannot be implemented without the people of Gibraltar voting yes in a referendum.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
