      <div class='hentry member_contribution'>
        <a name='S6CV0379P0_20020131_WH_89'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mrs-eleanor-laing' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S6CV0379P0_20020131_WH_89' title='Link to this speech by Mrs Eleanor Laing' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mrs-eleanor-laing" title="Mrs Eleanor Laing">Mrs. Laing</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            The hon. Gentleman has entirely missed the point. I wonder who told him to say that in the first place. He has, however, strangely echoed the point that I am about to make. I do not need to declare this, but some years ago I went to Gibraltar as a guest of the Government of Gibraltar. I have visited Gibraltar on many other occasions, as my cousin lives there. I spend a lot of time there and my impression of what the people of Gibraltar think about their current predicament comes directly from my cousin, her friends and
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_164wh' title='Col. 164WH &mdash; HC Deb 31 January 2002 vol 379 c164WH' name='column_164wh' href='#column_164wh' rel='bookmark'>164WH</a>
            associates, not from reading articles or being told by representatives of the Government of Gibraltar. That does not alter the fact that it is vital that Members of this House know what is going on there, as Gibraltar has no other voice. The people of Gibraltar are British and they deserve to be listened to as much as any British person living in the British isles or any other part of the world.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
